Anonymous Mon 29 Jun 2020 17:05:44 No.31204380 Report
Quoted By: >>31204681
>>31203716
Not much in some cases.
I'm working that out, and forgive me for the indulgence of self-promotion.
One of my beta readers for The Man From F.L.O.R.I.D.A. was a local romance/paranormal romance writer. I'll highlight a few bits of feedback.

Your female lead doesn't have to be all tough chick, but if you can't give her a hook the ladies can relate to, you're done. If Tahlia would have remained the same from first to last chapter, I'd have failed.

Second, you can't get away with making the guy flat. Drive the female lead with a touch of emotion, drive the guy with a touch of self-reliance and social convention. But let them be wrong in some way. The first draft had Jacob pushing back much less against Tahlia's snap decisions. His history of guilt and what seemed like the right thing evolved from a bunch of why and what-if questions.

Third, think about the vice versa from above. People make mistakes when they fumble their decisions. I'll throw Sharks in the mix here with his most recent update. The goal is to get a "oh crap you idiot, but I'd have made the same fuckup"; Phi_Fi likewise. It's a bit different skill in first person vs third, nor does it need to be readily apparent.

Fourth, a good side character. Think Vimes vs Carrot in Discworld, the warden vs the therapist in CotW, or Tahlia vs Leonora. Worldbuild all you want via the setting, but worldbuilding via your characters will nail it.

Really, all of this is base level stuff for longform fiction. Add in some of the stuff from the OP guides where appropriate, and hooking the ladies isn't any harder. You're giving the reader an escape. It's not your self-insert, but a chance for them to see bits of their self-image in many characters.

Whew. I should look up some of our conversations because I ravaged her first draft for a flat male lead. Likewise, he ended up far better after.
